25|$|As {{explained}} by Planck, a radiating body has an interior consisting of matter, and an interface with its contiguous neighbouring material medium, {{which is usually}} the medium from within which the radiation {{from the surface of}} the body is observed. The interface is not composed of physical matter but is a theoretical conception, a mathematical two-dimensional surface, a joint property of the two contiguous media, strictly speaking belonging to neither separately. Such an interface can neither absorb nor emit, because it is not composed of physical matter; but it is the site of reflection and transmission of radiation, because it is a <b>surface</b> <b>of</b> <b>discontinuity</b> of optical properties. The reflection and transmission of radiation at the interface obey the Stokes–Helmholtz reciprocity principle.|$|E
